#compdef myst
# =============================================================================
# myst — Jupyter Book project's "Command line tools for MyST
#        Markdown" — a TypeScript-Node CLI for authoring,
#        building, and previewing MyST (Markedly Structured
#        Text) documents.  MyST is a Markdown-superset
#        designed for scientific + technical publishing,
#        supporting LaTeX math, citations, cross-references,
#        executable code, figures with captions, admonitions,
#        roles, directives, and full reproducibility through
#        Jupyter integration.  The `myst` CLI replaces both
#        the older Sphinx + reStructuredText workflow for
#        Python scientific docs and the older Jupyter Book
#        Python toolchain.
#        Distinguishing from Sphinx, MkDocs, mdBook, Hugo,
#        and other docs generators by:
#          - MYST MARKDOWN SUPERSET — extends CommonMark with:
#              * Roles:      {role}`content`         e.g. {math}`E = mc^2`
#              * Directives: ```{directive} args
#                              content
#                            ```
#                            e.g. {admonition}, {figure},
#                            {table}, {note}, {warning},
#                            {tab-set}, {grid}, {card},
#                            {bibliography}, {tags}, etc.
#              * Cross-refs: [text](#anchor) or
#                            {ref}`section`
#              * Math:       $$E = mc^2$$ (display) or
#                            $x_n$ (inline; MathJax/KaTeX)
#              * Citations:  {cite}`Doe2020` from .bib file
#              * Footnotes:  [^1] and [^1]: footnote content
#              * Admonitions: :::{note} ... ::: (3-colon
#                             alternative to ``` fences)
#          - 5 ROOT COMMANDS via commander:
#              * init                — initialize new MyST project
#              * build                — build HTML / PDF / LaTeX
#              * start                — start dev server with HMR
#              * clean                — remove _build/ output
#              * templates            — manage MyST templates
#          - DUAL-FORMAT OUTPUT — same MyST source builds:
#              * HTML (default; static site or single page)
#              * PDF (via LaTeX + tectonic OR via
#                       Chromium headless)
#              * LaTeX (.tex source via jtex template engine
#                       — nunjucks-based)
#              * Word .docx (via pandoc backend)
#              * JATS XML (for journal submission)
#              * EPUB (for e-readers)
#              * Jupyter Book v1 compatibility
#          - JTEX TEMPLATE ENGINE — sibling sub-package using
#            nunjucks for LaTeX template rendering;
#            customizable templates for journal-specific
#            formatting (Elsevier, IEEE, Springer, etc.)
#          - LIVE PREVIEW via `myst start` — HMR dev server;
#            edit .md, see HTML update without refresh
#          - CITATION MANAGEMENT via citation-js-utils —
#            parse .bib / .json-csl files, render in-text
#            citations + bibliography section
#          - CROSS-REFERENCE GRAPH — myst-cli builds a graph
#            of all roles + directives + cross-references in
#            a project; unresolved refs flagged at build
#          - JUPYTER NOTEBOOK INTEGRATION — .ipynb files
#            treated as MyST sources; cells execute via
#            myst-execute sub-package
#          - JATS-TO-MYST conversion — sibling sub-package
#            ingests JATS XML (journal article XML format)
#            and emits MyST Markdown
#          - 50+ DIRECTIVE PACKAGES — myst-ext-button,
#            myst-ext-card, myst-ext-exercise, myst-ext-grid,
#            myst-ext-icon, myst-ext-tab, myst-ext-... — each
#            adds a custom directive to the parser
#          - YAML FRONT-MATTER for project + page config
#          - --config FILE — alternate myst.yml config path
#          - --debug flag — log errors verbosely
#          - WHITE-LABEL SUPPORT — companies can rebrand myst
#            as their own (Curvenote uses this; readableName
#            + isWhiteLabelled functions)
#        Used by: Jupyter Book v2+ users (NumPy / SciPy /
#        Pandas / scikit-learn books all migrating), academic
#        journals adopting JATS-compatible authoring (eLife,
#        bioRxiv preprints), scientific paper authors writing
#        reproducible research, and as a reference
#        implementation of nunjucks + commander + chalk + jtex
#        + JATS XML composition in TypeScript-Node.
#
# Author:  Rowan Cockett (rowan@curvenote.com) + Steve Purves
#          + Curvenote team — Jupyter Book project (sponsored
#          by 2i2c / Project Jupyter).  mystmd took over from
#          the older Python-only "Jupyter Book v1" in 2022.
#          Current version 1.9.1; active development through
#          2026.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/jupyter-book/mystmd
#          https://github.com/jupyter-book/mystmd/blob/main/packages/mystmd/src/index.ts
#          https://github.com/jupyter-book/mystmd/blob/main/packages/mystmd/package.json
#          https://github.com/jupyter-book/mystmd/blob/main/packages/jtex/package.json
#          https://mystmd.org (official docs)
# CLI:     packages/mystmd/src/index.ts — uses commander.
#          Headline library: **nunjucks** (used via the jtex
#          sub-package for LaTeX template rendering;
#          completing Axis 21 three-language symmetry
#          across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: nunjucks (https://github.com/mozilla/nunjucks —
#          "A powerful templating engine with inheritance,
#           asynchronous control, and more (jinja2 inspired)"
#           — James Long (jlongster) originally; now
#           maintained by Mozilla.  Distinct from tera (R673,
#           Rust Axis 21 opener) and pongo2 (R674, Go Axis 21
#           expansion) by being:
#              1. JINJA2-FAMILY SYNTAX IN JAVASCRIPT — nunjucks
#                 brings the same Jinja2/Django template
#                 syntax that tera (Rust) and pongo2 (Go)
#                 implement, to the Node.js ecosystem:
#                   <h1>Hello {{ name }}!</h1>
#                   {% for item in items %}
#                     <li>{{ item.name }} - {{ item.price | round(2) }}</li>
#                   {% endfor %}
#                   {% if user.isAdmin %}
#                     <a href="/admin">Admin Panel</a>
#                   {% endif %}
#                   {% include "partial.html" %}
#                   {% extends "base.html" %}
#                   {% block content %}{% endblock %}
#                 Token-for-token compatible with tera and
#                 pongo2; templates port directly between Rust /
#                 Go / TS-Node Jinja2-family engines.  This is
#                 the cross-language Jinja2 family.
#              2. ASYNC TEMPLATE EVALUATION — nunjucks's
#                 distinctive feature: templates can call
#                 ASYNC functions and resolve Promises:
#                   env.addFilter('fetchUser', async (id) => {
#                       return await db.getUser(id);
#                   }, true);  // mark as async
#                   nunjucks.renderString('{{ id | fetchUser }}',
#                       { id: 42 }, (err, res) => { ... });
#                 Distinct from tera + pongo2 + Jinja2 (sync-
#                 only).  Critical for Node.js where async
#                 I/O dominates.
#              3. MOZILLA MAINTENANCE — nunjucks moved to the
#                 Mozilla GitHub organization in 2015 (from
#                 jlongster).  Used by Mozilla Developer
#                 Network (MDN), Mozilla Foundation sites,
#                 etc.  Browser-compatible (works client-side
#                 + server-side).
#              4. INHERITANCE + INCLUDES + MACROS — full
#                 Jinja2 macro system:
#                   {% macro button(label, color='blue') %}
#                     <button class="btn-{{ color }}">{{ label }}</button>
#                   {% endmacro %}
#                   {{ button('Click me', color='red') }}
#                 Distinct from tera (also has macros) +
#                 pongo2 (limited macro support).
#              5. AUTO-ESCAPE BY DEFAULT (configurable) —
#                 nunjucks.configure('templates', {
#                     autoescape: true
#                 });  // HTML autoescape ON; `| safe` opt-out
#              6. ~30 BUILT-IN FILTERS — abs, batch, capitalize,
#                 center, default, dictsort, dump, escape, first,
#                 float, forceescape, groupby, indent, int, join,
#                 last, length, list, lower, nl2br, random,
#                 reject, rejectattr, replace, reverse, round,
#                 safe, select, selectattr, slice, sort, string,
#                 striptags, sum, title, trim, truncate, upper,
#                 urlencode, urlize, wordcount.  Custom filters
#                 via env.addFilter('name', fn).
#              7. TAGS — for / if / block / extends / include /
#                 macro / set / asyncEach / asyncAll / call /
#                 from / import / spaceless / raw / verbatim.
#                 Custom tags via env.addExtension.
#              8. BROWSER + NODE — same package runs in browsers
#                 + Node + Deno.  ~12KB minified for browser.
#                 Distinct from tera (Rust-only) and pongo2
#                 (Go-only).
#              9. PRECOMPILATION — nunjucks-precompile binary
#                 precompiles templates to JS for browser
#                 deployment (avoids template-parsing in
#                 production).
#             10. JAMES-LONG / MOZILLA NUNJUCKS-ORG
#                 ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — James Long (jlongster)
#                 originally authored nunjucks in 2012; now
#                 maintained by Mozilla volunteers.
#                 Distinct from Vincent Prouillet (tera /
#                 Keats — Rust), Florian Schlachter (pongo2
#                 — Go), Vitaly Puzrin (markdown-it / js-yaml).
#                 The "Jinja2-in-X" family across Rust + Go +
#                 Node represents a remarkable cross-
#                 language convergence on Armin Ronacher's
#                 original Python Jinja2 design.)
# License: BSD-2-Clause (nunjucks); MIT (mystmd)
# Status:  nunjucks — 8,964+ stars on mozilla/nunjucks, ~10M
#          weekly npm downloads (TOP-50 npm package by
#          downloads); foundational Jinja2-family Node
#          template engine used by:
#            * Mozilla Foundation websites
#            * Mozilla Developer Network (MDN)
#            * Eleventy (11ty static site generator default)
#            * Hexo (Node blog framework)
#            * Egg.js (Alibaba enterprise Node framework)
#            * Arco Design (ByteDance Vue UI library)
#            * Jupyter Book / mystmd (THIS)
#            * Vulcan SQL (Canner data API framework)
#            * 5000+ npm packages
#          mystmd — 503+ stars on jupyter-book/mystmd, used
#          by Jupyter Book v2+ scientific publishing.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 76 +
#                                                  AXIS 21 COMPLETES 1/1/1
#                                                  THREE-LANGUAGE SYMMETRY
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 76TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TS-Node climbs from 75
# to 76 documented libraries (nunjucks via myst).  TS-Node **catches
# Rust AND Go at 76** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=76 → eighth three-way tie at
# the leaderboard top in this round-sequence).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=76, Go=76, TypeScript-Node=76 (three-way tie at the top —
# perfect symmetry across all three leader languages).  Taxonomy
# now spans 407 cross-language CLI library variants across 100
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R673 Rust=76 (tera — Axis 21 OPENS) → R674 Go=76 (pongo2 —
# Axis 21 expands to 2) → R675 TS-Node=76 (nunjucks THIS — Axis 21
# completes 1/1/1 three-language symmetry) → expected R676 101st
# language.  This is the 3rd of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 21 (TEMPLATING ENGINES) to THREE
# documented variants — symmetrically distributed across Rust
# (tera R673), Go (pongo2 R674), and TS-Node (nunjucks THIS R675).
# Axis 21 becomes the FOURTEENTH AXIS to reach 1/1/1 three-
# language symmetry (joining Axes 7 / 8 / 11 / 12 / 15 / 16 / 17 /
# 18 / 19 / 20 + Axes 4 / 5 from earlier rounds).  Fourteen axes at
# three-language symmetry is a new taxonomy record.
#
# **JINJA2-FAMILY CROSS-LANGUAGE CONVERGENCE** — Axis 21's three
# variants (tera / pongo2 / nunjucks) all belong to the SAME
# Jinja2 syntax family:
#   - Rust:  tera     (Vincent Prouillet)
#   - Go:    pongo2   (Florian Schlachter)
#   - Node:  nunjucks (James Long / Mozilla)
# All inherit from Armin Ronacher's 2008 Python Jinja2 template
# engine syntax.  Templates port directly between the three with
# minor differences (filter argument syntax).  Remarkable cross-
# language convergence on one design tradition.
#
#   Axis 21 (TEMPLATING ENGINES) variants:
#     - tera (Keats/tera) — R673 (_rag) — Rust Jinja2 templates;
#       runtime-compiled; serde Context; ~60 filters;
#       Vincent Prouillet / Keats ecosystem
#     - pongo2 (flosch/pongo2) — R674 (_linx-server) — Go Django/
#       Jinja2 templates; reflection-based context; ~50 Django
#       filters; Florian Schlachter / flosch ecosystem
#     - nunjucks (mozilla/nunjucks) — R675 (THIS) — Node Jinja2
#       templates; ASYNC template evaluation (distinctive);
#       browser-compatible; ~30 filters; James Long / Mozilla
#       ecosystem
#
# Three Axis 21 variants share THE SAME SYNTAX FAMILY but
# differ in language-specific features:
#   tera               = Rust serde integration; sync; ~60 filters
#   pongo2             = Go reflection; sync; ~50 Django filters
#   nunjucks           = Node ASYNC eval; browser+server; ~30 filters
#
# Each variant adds language-idiomatic features beyond Jinja2's
# Python original:
#   - tera adds:    Rust serde Context (typed serialization)
#   - pongo2 adds:  Go reflection-based dotted-path lookup
#   - nunjucks adds: ASYNC template evaluation (Promise-aware)
#
# Axis 21 distribution: Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=1.  Three-language
# symmetry achieved at 1/1/1.
#
# Axis distribution summary after R675:
#   * Axis 1  (Argparse):     Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 4  (Colors):       Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 5  (Progress):     Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 6  (Errors):       Rust=6  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 7  (Boxes):        Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 8  (Prompts):      Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 9  (Logging):      Rust=6  / Go=6  / TS-Node=6   (6/6/6)
#   * Axis 10 (Tables):       Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2   (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 11 (Humanization): Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 12 (Text Wrap):    Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 13 (Config Files): Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2   (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 14 (Paths):        Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2   (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 15 (Date/Time):    Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 16 (HTTP Clients): Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 17 (File Watching): Rust=1 / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 18 (WebSockets):    Rust=1 / Go=1  / TS-Node=1   (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 19 (Markdown Parsing): Rust=1 / Go=1 / TS-Node=1 (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 20 (YAML Parsing):     Rust=1 / Go=1 / TS-Node=1 (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 21 (Templating Engines): Rust=1/Go=1/TS-Node=1   (1/1/1) NEW
#
# Jinja2-family cross-language note:
#   Armin Ronacher's 2008 Python Jinja2 template syntax has
#   become the lingua franca of templating across multiple
#   languages.  Axis 21 documents the three major language
#   adaptations:
#     * Python:  Jinja2          — Armin Ronacher (original)
#     * Rust:    tera             — Vincent Prouillet         (R673)
#     * Go:      pongo2           — Florian Schlachter        (R674)
#     * Node:    nunjucks         — James Long / Mozilla      (THIS)
#   Armin Ronacher (mitsuhiko) is ALREADY a documented author
#   via dialoguer (R661 — Axis 8 — Prompts).  Through the
#   indirect Jinja2 inheritance of tera/pongo2/nunjucks, Armin's
#   influence reaches ALL THREE Axis 21 entries.  Direct authorship
#   of Axis 21 is split across Vincent Prouillet (Rust),
#   Florian Schlachter (Go), and James Long / Mozilla (Node) —
#   but conceptually Armin Ronacher's Jinja2 is the family
#   patriarch.
#
# (Leaderboard at R675: Rust=76, Go=76, TS-Node=76 — EIGHTH
# three-way tie at 76 in this round-sequence.  Axis 9 / Logging
# 6/6/6 three-way symmetric.  Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.
# Axes 7 + 8 + 11 + 12 + 15 + 16 + 17 + 18 + 19 + 20 + 21 at
# 1/1/1.  FOURTEEN axes at three-language symmetry — most
# balanced state in taxonomy history, beating the prior R671
# record of thirteen axes.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE myst CLI — commander + nunjucks (via jtex) + JATS + Jupyter
#
# myst's CLI is in packages/mystmd/src/index.ts.  Uses commander
# for argv parsing with 5 root subcommands.
#
# Source:
#     import { Command } from 'commander';
#     const program = new Command();
#     program.addCommand(makeInitCLI(program));
#     program.addCommand(makeBuildCLI(program));
#     program.addCommand(makeStartCLI(program));
#     program.addCommand(makeCleanCLI(program));
#     program.addCommand(makeTemplatesCLI(program));
#     program.version(version, '-v, --version', ...);
#     program.option('-d, --debug', '...');
#     program.option('--config <config-file>', '...');
#     addDefaultCommand(program);
#     program.parse(process.argv);
#
# Subcommands (5):
#   init                   initialize new MyST project
#   build [options]        build HTML / PDF / LaTeX / etc.
#   start [options]        start dev server with HMR
#   clean                  remove _build/ output
#   templates              manage MyST templates
#
# Global flags:
#   -v, --version          show version
#   -d, --debug            log errors verbosely
#   --config FILE          alternate myst.yml config path
#   -h, --help             show help (commander default)
#
# nunjucks is used by the sibling jtex sub-package for LaTeX
# template rendering.  When `myst build --tex` or
# `myst build --pdf` is invoked, jtex loads .tex.njk templates
# and renders them via nunjucks with project metadata
# (title, authors, citations, content).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from tera (R673) + pongo2 (R674):
#
#   1. JINJA2 SYNTAX IN JAVASCRIPT — same syntax family as
#      tera + pongo2 but JavaScript-native runtime.
#
#   2. ASYNC TEMPLATE EVALUATION — Promise-aware filters +
#      tags; distinctive to nunjucks.
#
#   3. BROWSER + NODE — same package runs client-side +
#      server-side.
#
#   4. PRECOMPILATION via nunjucks-precompile CLI — JS
#      output for browser deployment.
#
#   5. JAMES-LONG / MOZILLA ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — distinct
#      maintainer; Mozilla volunteer-driven.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/jupyter-book/mystmd/blob/main/packages/mystmd/src/index.ts
# commander Command + addCommand + option / version definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _myst_cmds
_myst_cmds=(
    'init:initialize a new MyST project'
    'build:build HTML / PDF / LaTeX / etc. from MyST sources'
    'start:start dev server with HMR live preview'
    'clean:remove _build/ output directory'
    'templates:manage MyST templates (list / add / remove)'
    'help:show help for a subcommand'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
    '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[log errors verbosely]' \
    '--config=[alternate myst.yml config path]:file:_files -g "*.(yml|yaml)"' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'myst subcommand' _myst_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            build)
                _arguments \
                    '--html[build HTML output (default)]' \
                    '--pdf[build PDF output (via LaTeX or Chromium)]' \
                    '--tex[build LaTeX output]' \
                    '--docx[build Word .docx output (via pandoc)]' \
                    '--jats[build JATS XML output]' \
                    '--meca[build MECA archive]' \
                    '--site[build full static site]' \
                    '--all[build all configured formats]' \
                    '--force[force rebuild ignoring cache]' \
                    '--watch[watch sources and rebuild on change]' \
                    '*:source file:_files -g "*.(md|ipynb)"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            start)
                _arguments \
                    '--port=[dev server port]:port:_default' \
                    '--host=[dev server host]:host:_default' \
                    '--keep-host[do not override host setting]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            templates)
                _values 'templates action' 'list' 'add' 'remove' && ret=0
                ;;
            help)
                _describe -t commands 'subcommand' _myst_cmds && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
